{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_bellatrix_ver03/data/sn89075140/00415665945/1930042501/0122.xml":{"full_text":"y\nr'A\nMinnick\nPasses In Death\nEmanuel Mtnnick, 83, an aged\nresident of Washington Twp. Hen*\nry county, passed away at his home\non Thursday morning-, a victim of\n'l. pneumonia.\nFuneral services will be held at\nthe home of his son, Earl Minnick\nin Grand Rauids on Saturday a*\n3:00 p. m. Burial at Mt. Pleasant.\nFred Gill, Funeral Director.\n\nv\n5 Control Apple\nScab Early\n4a ~6J<\nIt is possible by thorough spray\ning with standard materials to con\ntrol almost completely apple, scab\nduring the pre-blossom period.'The\nfungus causing the disease lives\nover the winter in the old apple\nleaves. During this off .season it\n\u25a0\u25a0i grows slowly, and by the time the\nv apple leaves and blossoms start it\nproduces spores. Usually,.the spores\nare all mature during this early\nblooming period, and timely spray\ning will prevent disease. This year\nthe spores of the apple'scab fungus\nhre maturing very early. Some of\nthem have already been discharged\nand 60 per cent are now mature for\nthe delayed dormant period. While\nconsiderable Infection can take\nplace during the delayed dormant\nthe more critical period this year\nis the one Just'following, providing\na rain period develops. At this time\niL the buds are unfpiding rapidly and\na spray pay not be effective fur\ns' more than 48 hours Since infection,\ntakes place only during rainy wea\nther, it is better to apply the spray\n.Just ahead of a ptodicted rain per-:\niod. In case no such period is pre\nVi: dieted, spray when the blossom\n6 .dusters unfold and Just before they:\n'bloom.\nThe material recommended for\nthe pre-blossom period is dry lime\nsulphur, 3% pounds to 50 gallons\nof water, or liquid lime-sulphur,\nkr; 1-40. The dusts recommended are\nsulphUFrdry lime-sulphur 85-15, or\nsulphur-manganar dust.\nSpicey Squibs\nby Walter Spicer Farm Editor\nHeat and Bad Eggs\np Title Is not a discourse on crim-,\ninalogy nor does it pertain to the\nslight effect of returning spring\nweather upon .young mens' fancies\nbut rather of hens\u2019 eggs or what\nhave yon.\nSummer heat has the same effect\non fertile eggs as the Jien or incu\nbator. The fertile germ in hot wea\nther develops into a blood ring/\nwhich spoils the egg for food or\nmarket purposes. Heat is the great\nenemy-of eggs both fertile and in\nfertile. On this account during the\nwarm weather, egg producers are\nurged to keep nests clean and to\nprovide one nest for every four\nfowls, in order that the nests will\nnot be used too often and soil the\neggs, to gather the eggs twice daily\nto keep the eggs in a cool, dry\nroom or cellar, to market the\nI eggs at least twice a week, and to\npen or dispose of all roosters as\nsoon as the hatching season is over,\nr\u2019iv Hens isolated, on range from the\nI maie produce infertile eggs of de\nP gtrable quality. In general, about\ntwo weeks after the roosters are\nremoved from the flock, the hens\nwill yield infertile eggs.\nScenic Highway r.\nIll Ass\u2019n To Dine\nA membership dinner will be\nheld at the Elks\u2019 Club at Defiance\non Tuesday evening, April 29, at\n6:30 p. m. in connection with tlje\nmeeting of the executive committee\nof the Maumee River Scenic and\nHistoric Association.\nThe dinner is under the auspices\nof the Defiance Chamber of Com\nmerce. Chas. H. Lewis of the Ohio\nConservation Council will be the\n\u2022principal speaker.\nThose who are Interested in se\ncuring parks along the old Mau\nmee should show their interest by\nattending this banquet. Tickets\niy be secured at the Grand Rap\nBank at fl. each.\nThe Plus Ultra Class will hold\nits regular monthly business and\nsocial meeting at the home of Mrs.\nAlta Hutchinson on Wednesday af\n^ternoon, April 30.\nMrs. Jessie Miller and sister,\nHattie entertained at Easter din-4\nper Mr. and Mrs. Guy Miller and\nfamily and Wm. Bowers of Grand\nRapids, and Mr. and Mrs. Fred\nHUItt Of Waterville.\nHave you returned Sterling\u2019s\nmilk bottles and reminded your\nneighbor to do likewise?\nV t. 1\nWORLD WAR VETS. TO PLAY\nAT RIVERBY HILM COURSE\nThe Toledo Post No. 335 .have\ninvited the McCune Post to play at\nthe Riverby Hills Golf Course, on\nThursday, May 8th, is the announ\ncement made by Chet O\u2019Connor,\nmanager of the Goif Course. i\nAfter the game, the veterans will\nrepair to Galbraith. Island for their\nbanquet and entertainment. Toledo\nPest of the American Legion owqs\nGalbraith Island and the Legion\nboys hold the major portion of\ntheir doings on their \u201cIsland\u201d\nwhich is just across the river from\nRiverby Hills.\nThe .officers of the Toledo Post\nCarl M. Eyster, Commander,\nL. L. Morris, Adjutant.\nEntertains\nMr. and Mrs. Alvin Keister en\ntertained a number of their friends\nfrom Haskins, with a supper given\nat 7i30 Saturday evening. The\nguests were: Mr. and Mrs. Ray\nVollmar and daughters Bernice and\nViola; Mr. and Mrs. Chas. Walker\nand daughter Flora Grace; Mr. and\nMrs. Lawrence Sutton and daugh\nter Alice Jay; Mr. and Mrs. Geo.\nWalker and daughters Marvella\nand Gloria Mae; Mrs. Geo. Sutton,'\nMr. and Mrs. Henry Schaller and\nsons Ronald and Norman; Mr. and\nMrs: Adam Bohel; Mr. and Mrs.\nArthur Rothgeb and daughter Thel\nma of Grand Rapids; Mr. and Mrs.\nCarl Keister and son Donald of\nColumbus.\nv\nExchange News\nThe regular meeting of the Ex\nchange Club of Grand Rapids, given\nover to the entertainment of the\nladies, was held in the Woodman\nHall.\nAbout one hundred and ten were\npresent and enjoyed a very- nice re\npast, served by the, ladies of the\nMethodist Church.\nHoratio S. Earle, was the speak\ner of the evening and gave a very\ninteresting .speech on \u201cThe Boot\nMan\u201d.\nWm. Dunlpace, district Governor\nof Dictrict No. 8 spoke and announ\nced that there would be a district\nand charter meeting at Findlay. He\nhoped that there would be a large\nturn out from Grand Rapids at the\nmeeting, as, Grand Rapids Exchange\nClub was to be presented with the\npenant for sponsoring the Club.\nCharles Martin as usual was pre\nsent and entertained all present.\nEach lady present was presented\nwith a favor and we all hope that\nall who were' present will return\nat the next Ladies Night, to be\nheld in about six months from now.\nThis Doesn\u2019t\nLook Good\nFor Cooper\nby Elmer P. Fries\nMore than 2200 state owned mo\ntor vehicles are being operated by\nthe Administration of Gov. M- Y.\nCooper, according to license records\nof the secretary of state. In the\npreceding administration, 1864\nsuch vehicles were in use, accord\ning to figures cited by Gov. Cooper\nin campaign speeches. The figures\ninclude both trucks and passenger\ncars.\n\"This increase of more than 300\napparently is to be swelled this\nyear, \u201cDemocratic state headquar\nters commented today in presenting\nthe comparative figures and point\ning to the fact that \"the state high\nway department announced on Feb\nruary 26 it had let contracts for 85\ntrucks at $325,000 and on March\n15 it had let contracts for 200\ntrucks at $221,830, allowances to\nbe made in some instances for old\ntrucks.\"\n\u201cAdditions have been made in\nthe number of commercial cars and\nin the number of high priced plea\nsure cars in spite of Governor Coop\ner\u2019s repeated' pre-election attacks\non motor vehicle oparation under\nhis predecessor and his promises\nto effect economies in such expen\nditures,\u201d continued the headquar\nters statement.\n\u201cLet\u2019s see what Cooper as a can\ndidate for office said. This quota\ntion is taken from a reliable news\npaper account reporting his cam\npaign speeches: Cooper hammered\non what he declares is the impera\ntive need for genuine economy and\nreal business management in the\naffairs of state government. He cit\ned the purchase of autos by the\nstate as one of the glaring exam\nples of extravagance and said it is\ncosting the taxpayers thousands of\nIs Hoover's\nProphecy Right\nW. W. Durbin, Candidate for the\nDemocratic nomination for United\nStates Senator, in his speech at the\nDemocratic Banquet at Napoleon,.\nOhio, April 22, 1930, said in part:\n\u201cPresident Hoover has set May\nfifteenth as the date for the return\nof prosperity, and every person in\nAmerica sincerely hopes that his\nprophecy might come true. Unfor\ntunately, however, promises and\npropaganda, are not improving the\nsituation. First of all, business, la\nbor and agriculture in the United\nStates must realize the truth of the\nsituation, else there can be no real\nremedy.\n\"Dun\u2019s Review, a weekly survey\nof business conditions in the United\nStates and Canada, portrays a pic\nture that cannot be ignored longer.\nIt shows for instance, that building\noperations in this country have fal\nlen off 55 per cent this year as com\npared with last year, which was a\nbad year in the building trade. In\nthe months of January, February\nand March, 1929. building permits\namounted to $663. 994.900. In the\nsame period of 1930, the amount of\nbuilding permits fell to $291,329.\n10,0.\n\u201cThese regrettable figures ex\nplain in some degree why more\nthan four million men and women\nare out of work in the U. S.: why\nthere are breadlines in the cities:\nwhy merchants, manufacturers and\nfarmers in unprecedented number\nare failing. There were 881 more\nfailures during the first three\nmonths of this year than during the'\nsame period of 1929, with liabilit\nies of $45,000,000 more than last\nyear. During this same period in\n1930, 124 banks failed, with liabil\nities'of almost $52,00(17000 as com\npared with 81 bank failures during\nthe first three months of 1929, with\nliabilities of $37,000,000.\n\"One of the causes of the present\nunfortunate business depression\nwas the continuous prosperity\nnropaganda that lulled the people\ninto a fool's paradise and sought\nto convince them that the U. S. had\ncome into a new Hoover economic\nera in which business depression\nwas impossible. The administration\nat Washington must tell people the\ntruth and stop its propaganda if\nbusiness, labor and agriculture Is\nto go forward upon a sound econ\nomic basis.\u201d\ndollars needlessly in the upkeep of\nthe immense fleet now owned by the\nhighway department. \"Many of the\ncars are of expensive make,\" Coop\ner said. \u201cThat is usless extravagance\nHalf a million dollars could easily\nbe saved by giving the men the\nkind of cars they should have and\nnot buying the most expensive kind.\nThat is one thing I propose to stop\nwhen I become Governor.\u201d\n\u201cNow let\u2019s see what has happened\nunder Cooper as Governor. The di\nrector of highways Is Piloted a Cad\nillac sedan which is guaranteed to\nminimize the effects of any bumps\nthere may be in roads under his\njurisdiction. A Studebaker sedan\ncosting $1950 Is bought for the\ndirector of finance and a chauf\nfeur paid .$1440 a year by the\nstate, is thrown in. A Wlllys Kni\nght sedan also is purchased for the\nfinance director\u2019s department. To\nthe director of welfare is assigned\na Studebaker sedan, to the direc\ntors of industrial relations and pub\nlic works go Buick sedans. And so\non through the long list of officials\nsome of them engaged in duties j\nwhich formerly were not consid\nered as requiring automobile trans\nportation. In the highway depart\nment are dozens of such cars as\nBuick sedans Chandlers, Hupps,\nStudebakers, all above the low\nprice ranges which taxpayers were\nled to believe would be adhered to\nif candidate Cooper were elected\nGovernor.\nWith these cars go gasoline,\ntires, car washings, repairs and the\nlike at the taxpayers\u2019 expense and\nuse of them is not restricted to of\nficial duties.\n\u201cIn his campaign speeches Gov\nernor Cooper complained that there\nwere too many limousines, sedans\nand coupes, used by the state em\nployes .for whose purposes touring\ncars and roadsters would suffice.\nToday the modest touring car and\nroadster are almost obsolete. The\nmore comfortable and luxurious\nsedan, coupe, coach and brougham\nare preferred by state office hold\ners who enjoy motoring ease.\n\u201cThe blunt truth is that the\n\"half million dollars a year\u201d, that\nCandidate Cooper said \u2018easily could\nbe saved\u201d is not being saved by\nGovernor Cooper.-Not yet has a\nratio of one car to every job been\nattained, but both cars and jobs\nhave been increased.\u201d\nMrs. Kate Warner entertained at\nher home near McClure, on Easter\nSunday: Mr. and Mrs. Frank Fet\nterman of Liberty Center, Mr. and\nMrs. S. H. King of Grand Rapids\nand the Misses Alvlrda Alice and\nNorma Crowell of McClure.\nCantata'\nThe M. E. church invites you to\nattend the Cantata to be given by\nthe Union Choir of Weston, on Sun\nday evening, at 7:30. No admission\ncharge.\n\nBlames Tariff\nFor Depression\n\nW. W. Durbin, Candidate for the\nDemocratic nomination for U. S.\nSenator issued the following state\nment: \u201cAs a business man and a\nmanufacturer I challenge Senator\nMcCulloch\u2019s position upon the\nGrundy tariff bill, for which'he vo\nted and which he is defending upon\nthe stump. Let me remind'Mr. Mc\nCulloch that the unfortunate de\npression we are paw experiencing,\nwith its millions of unemployed,\ncame under the highest tariff rates\never in force in the United States;\nwhich rates the Grundy tijlil will\nraise even higher. What thfe Ameri\ncan manufacturer needs today is\nnot more protection but k wider\nmarket.\n\u201cAlready the detrimental results\nof the Grundy tariff bill are being\nfelt by American business. Amerir\ncan farmers and American labor;\nAll over Europe tnd in Australia,\ntariff rates are being raised against\nAmerican products in retaliation.\nAustralia, for instance, has been\nbuying about one hundred and fif\nty millions of dollars worth of\ngoods from us, five times as much\nas we buy from her, but has now\nset out to enact a tariff law that\nwill practically prohibit most of\nour commodities.\n\"American manufacturers are\nbeing forced by circumstances to\nbuild branch plants all over the\nworld, thereby narrowing. the mar\nket for goods made in the U. S.I\nneed only to point out the plants of\nHenry Ford In England, Germany,\nand France, and his tractor plant\nIn Ireland, where tractors are made\nby foreign labor and then shipped\nto the United States free of any\ntariff duty as agricultural products\n\"Senator McCulloch and Sena\ntor Grundy are living In the past.\nThey do not seem to realise that\nmass production in the U^ be*\nrevolutionised- Atfiericgn manufac\nturing and its relation to the rest\nof the world. Adequate markets,\nnot the Grundy bill, will mean a\nreturn of prosperity to the manu\nfacturers, laboring people and far\nmers of the United States. Under\nthe present tariff law we find Am\nerican capital in foreign countries\nemploying foreign labor in compet\nition with American labor ia Amer\nican factories. The Grundy tariff\nlaw will hurt, not help, American\nbusiness and American labor.\"\nThe will of the late Albert Bell\nleaves all personal property, after,\nall debts are paid, to his wife,\nMargaret Bell. The real estate also\ngoes to her during her lifetime,\nafter which it goes to the children,\nGrace Marie Bell Carter, Albert\nLloyd .Bell and Paul William Bell,\nshare and share alike.\nHe also appointed his wife as\nexecutrix of the estate without\nbond.\nAs long as they last, women\u2019s\nblack and brown hose, suitable for\nhouse-cleaning and gardening. 12c\na pair, 3 pairs for 35c. The Bell\nStore.\nMrs. Calvin' Miser, Jessie Graff\nand Clarence Miser visited the for\nmer\u2019s daughter, Margery Myers and\nfamily at Rudolph, on Sunday af\nternoon.\nMr. Lawrence Brown, Lowell\nStuder, Howard Winters and Em\nery Perry attended the show at To\nledo, Friday.\nMrs. John Souders, who has. been\nsuffering} from an attack of the flu,\nis better at this writing!.\nJohn Williams and family of\nPayette, O., have moved on the\nClate Jeffers farm north of town.\nJack Benschoter and boy friend\nof Toledo, visited from Thursday\nuntil Sunday with his uncle, How\nard Benschoter and wife.\nMr. and Mrs. Ray Sherwood and\nDesmond, were Toledo shoppers,\nFriday.\nRoy Height of Perrysburg, spent\nMohday with Paul Herman.\nMr. and Mrs. Basil Sparling of\nLoudfnville, were guests of Mr.\nand Mrs. Lee Hey man from Friday\nuntil Sunday afternoon. In the af\nternoon they were guests of Mr.\nand Mrs. Burl Dull at McClure,\nand on Monday they visited in the\nJake Croll home at Tontogany;\nafter which they returned to their\nhome.\nMr. and Mrs. Paul Crawford of\nBowling Green spent Easter Sun\nday with her parents, Mr. and Mrs.\nH. W. Hutchinson.\nOpening Dance\nBig Success\nRegardless of the down-pour of\nrain the American Legion dance at\nGrand Rapids opened at 8:30 p. m.\nEaster, with a full house, about\nfour hundred people present for the\nevening.\nTylors orchestra with his won\nderful male entertainers, furnished\nthe music for the round dances,\nplaying the latest hits and class\nical numbers. Mr. Gingrich, who\nplayed the lions share of the square\ndances, is one of the Legion boys\nand when it comes to real square\nmusic, he certainly has it.\nThe first square dance was a\nreal knock-out, a double grand\nmarch, directed by Sam Dull of\nMcClure, manager of the successful\ndance of Grelton, where fifteen\nhundred persons passed through\nthe doors in six Saturday nights.\nThe dance was well managed by\nthe boys, they had wonderful order\nand everybody enjoyed themselves\nthroughout the entire evening\nwhich came to a quiet close at 12\no\u2019clock, with everyone wishing the\nboys continued success.\nHere\u2019s Dope On\nAuto Races\nToledo, Ohio, April 24\u2014Having\nreceived a sanction from the Amer\nican Automobile Association Con\ntest Board to run a triple A. Auto\nRace at Ft. Miami mile track, To\nledo on Sunday May 25, B. Ward\nBeam, who has handled the track\nfor the past nine years announced\nyesterday that the event would be\n100 miles.\nBeam has, for some time had\nunder consideration the advisabil\nity of running shorter sprint events\nhaving had a number of fans make\nsuch request, but he now feels\nthat the response from those op\nposed to the sprint variety justi-\nfies the continuance of the century\ngrinds that have become so popur i\nlar in the nine years they have\nbeen run.\nEntry blanks will go in the mail\nwithin the next few days and the\nmanager assures the race fans that\nthe greatest' array of talent ever\nto enter the spring classic will be\n1 on hand. Many of the Indianapolis\nSpeedway stars are expected to en\nter, and there will be no increase 1\nin prices.\nM. E. Program\nThe committee in charge of the\nEaster entertainment, and those\ntaking part, are to be commended\non the fine program which they\nhad prepared for Easter; also the\ndecorating committee for the dec\norations. The cross in the back\nground and the platform banked\nwith flowers was very beautiful\nand appropriate.\nThe Sunday school orchestra is\nto be congratulated on the fine\nmusic which was rendered\" by them.\nA good attendance was present.\nArbor Day\nArbor Day has been fixed by\nproclamation of Governor My\u00aers Y.\nCooper ftr \\pril 25th. All schools\nof the state are ordered by law to\ndevote at least two hours In that\nday to consideration of tree plant\ning, nature study and conservation.\nArbor Day programs may be had\nfree from the Conservation Divis\nion, Department of Agriculture, at\nColumbus.\nA good thing to remember,\nA better thing to do\u2014\nWork with the construction gang\nAnd not with the wrecking crew.\nMr. and Mrs. Frederick Miser\nand daughter Kathryn of Genoa,\nspent Sunday with Mr. and Mrs.\nFred Kirian.\nMr. and Mrs. Wm. Herman en\ntertained at an Easter dinner on\nSunday, Mrs. Henry Lake and Mr.\nand Mrs. Jaqua of Deshler. After\nnoon callers were, Mr. and Mrs.\nFrancis Scott and family of Ton\ntogany.\nMiss Arlene Gill accompanied\nMay Manor to Toledo last Satur\nday.\nMrs. Dudley of Columbus, has\ncome to stay with her father, Mar\ntin White. Mr. Dudley and daugh\nters spent Thursday night with\nthem, returning to their home in\nColumbus on Friday morning.\nChester Box and family and D\nW. Box. spent Easter Sunday with\nMrs. Mae Johnston.\nMr. and Mrs. Dayle Wolf spent\nSunday evening at Toledo.\nMartin White is building a gar\nage on his property on Bridge St.\nChas. White of Toledo, is assisting\nwith the work.\nENTERPRISE GRANGE NEWS\nThere will be Grange at Enter\nprise this Thursday evening, 24th.\nand the special meeting has been\npostponed until next Monday even\ning 28th., when the. Bowling Green\nteam will put on the work and will\ntake in a class of 7 candidates. All\nGrangers are urged to be present\nat these meetings.\nEASTER LUNCHEON\nThe Missionary Tea held at the\nPresbyterian church on Thursday j\nafternoon was well attended, guests\nbeing present from Weston and Ton\ntogany. Plates were laid for 49,\nafter which, a delightful Easter\nprogram was rendered as follows:\nPresiding officer\u2014Pearl Gill\nOpening Song\u2014In The Garden.\nPrayer\u2014Mrs. Kuder\n\u201cOld Days\u201d\u2014Remarks by Mrs. Pull\ner, charter member of our society.\nSong\u2014Richard Box\nReading\u2014The Way The Master\nWent, by Mrs. A. Box.\nEaster Customs In The Holy Land\nby Mrs. E. Souders.\nMusic\u2014Roland and Mrs. Ruth\nStrayer.\nReading\u2014\u201cVery Early In The\nMorning\" by Miss Lucille Boulton.\nThoughts On Easter\u2014Mrs. King.\nMusic\u2014 Robert and Mrs. Ruth\nStrayer.\nReading\u2014The Beautiful Descrip\ntion Of The Resurection, Math. 28\n2to 9; closing with the \u201cGreat Com\nmission,\u201d Math. 28- 18, 19 and 20.\nClosing Hymn\u2014Up From The\nGrave He Arose.\nPrayer for Mrs. prank Sheats.\nBenediction\u2014Rev. Myers.\nTAKE NOTICE!\nSpeed limit for business section,\n20 miles per hour. On Second St.*\nwhich is public highway, 35 miles\nner hour within city limits. Beware\nof time speed trap!\nJohn Painter, Marshal\nNapoleon, Ohio\u2014Mrs. Margaret\nBell has been appointed and qual\nified as executrix of the estate of\nthe late Albert Bell.\nJudge Cahill\nDon\u2019t forget we are selling a\nman\u2019s regular $1.00 Athletic Un\nion Suit\u2014all sizes\u2014for 79c each,\nor 2 for $1.50. The Bell Store.\nMr. and Mrs. John Painter Were\nIn Toledo, Wednesday afternoon.\nMr. and Mrs. Clyde Bortel were\nat Auburn, Ind., on Monday.\nRemember the Plus Ultra party\nat Alta Hutchinson\u2019s on Wednesday\nMay 30; also Missionary meeting\nat the home of Mrs. John Tonjes,\nMay 8.\nFred Gill and family entertained\nat dinner, Easter Sunday, Miss May\nMay nor, Howard Haas of Custar\nand Ford Murry of Liberty Center.\nMr. and Mrs. Welter France and\nsons of Detroit, were guests of Will\nis Jackson and family.\nDale Murrey of Detroit spent his\nEaster vacation with Mr. and Mrs.\nN. Murrey.\nRUN DOWN BY AUTO\nWhat might have been a serious\naccident occurred Friday at 8:45\np. m., near the Johnson Gas Sta\ntion, when Laird Johnston, driving\neast, ran down the young son of\nKeith Black of Neapolis, as he\nbounded from between parked cars\nto cross the street to' the north\nside. Luckily, the Johnson car was\ntraveling slowly and the boy re\nceived only a few slight cuts and\nbruises.\nNo one has, as yet, been killed\nor seriously hurt by automobiles in\nthis town which, to our way of\nthinking, signifies an alert people\nrather than careful drivers.\nMrs. Clem Krout and Mrs. Clyde\nBortel attended a show at Toledo,\nFriday night.\nCleo Katon and family were Sun\nday dinner guests of Mr. and Mrs.\nWm. Katon.\nJnlla Backus of Bowling Green\nNormal, attended the Exchange\nClub Banquet on Wednesday night.\nMrs. Mae Hathaway was the Sun\nday dinner guest of Mr. and Mrs.\nWalter Mitchel at Toledo.\nRuby Barton of Weston visited\nGrand Rapids school, Friday.\nArrested For Open Cut-out\nDonald Katon was arrested on\nSaturday night by Marshal Painter,\nfor operating a car with open cut\nout. He was taken before Mayor\nBox where he pleaded guilty as\ncharged and was given a suspended\nsentence for first offense.\nSecond offense means a fine of\nnot less than $10. and costs with\nlicense taken away for six months\nor more.\nSurprised On\nEaster Sunday\nA very enjoyable day was spent\non Easter Sunday at the A. W.\nKrout home when their children\nand grand-children surprised them\nby gathering with well filled bas\nkets, for a family dinner.\nThose who enjoyed this very\npleasant occasion were: Mrs. Perry\nRichmond and children of Napol\neon; Mr. and Mrs. Fred Krout and\nson Harod; Mr. and Mrs. Carl\nKrout and sons; Mr. and Mrs. Otis\nFuller of Toledo; Mr. and Mrs.\nRalph Ward and children of Mc\nClure; Mr. and Mrs. Dick Witte\nand son of Waterrille; Grant Mund\nwiler of Hoytville; clem Grout and\nfamily and Mr. and Mrs. A. W.\nKrout.\nComing Events\nApril 2S, School closes for the\ngrades.\nApril 25, 8th grade commence\nment.\nApril 26, Library Tag Day.\nApril 2? Cantata at M. E. Church\nat 7:30.\nApril 30, Plus Ultra Party at the\nHutchinson home.\nApril 30, sophmore play.\nMay 1st. Culture Club Luncheon\nat the Womans\u2019 Building at Bow\nling Green.\nMay 1, High School Party.\nMay 2, BalJ game, Haskins there.\nMay 5 Parent Teachers\u2019 meeting.\nMay 8, Presbyterian Missionary\nat Mrs. John Tonjes\u2019s home.\nMay 9 Base ball game, Tontog\nany, there.\nMay 16, Senior Class Play.\nMay 19 to 23, Commencement\nweek.\nMay 24, Annual Plus Ultra Birth\nday party.\nJune 12, Rebekah Convention at\nthis place. T\nLodge Calandar\nWoodman, Monday night.\n0. E. L.f first and third Tues\nday night.\n1. O. O. P. Camp, first and third\nTuesday night.\nMasons, second and fourth Tues\nday night.\nExchange Club, second and\nfourth Wednesday at 6 p. m.\nAmerican Legion second and\nfourth Wednesday night.\nAmerican Legion Auxiliary, sec- v',\nond and fourth Wednesday night.\nRebekahs every Thursday night.\nRelief Corps, Friday afternoon.\nRoyal Neighbors, every Friday\nnight.\nPRESBYTERIAN CHURCH\nRev. J. W. Myers, Pastor\nSunday School, 9:30\nM. E. CHURCH\nRev. A. G. Jenkins, Pastor\nSunday School, 9:30\nPreaching 10:30\nCantata 7:30\nEpworth League 6:30\nIF YOU WANT PARKS\u2014\nMAKE IT KNOWN\nThose who are interested in get\nting parks along the maumee river\nshould show their interest by at\ntending the banquH at Defiance,\nApril 29. Chairman Chas. H. Lewis\nof the Ohio Conservation Commis\nsion will be impressed with the pro\nject in proportion to the interest\nshown; and to greet him as the\nspeaker there will be one way to\nimpress him deeply. Don\u2019t take it\nfor granted that we will get such\nparks without working for them.\nCalvin Miser visited his brother\nat Alma, Mich., over the week end.\nMr. Howard Hastings visited\nfrom Friday until Monday with rel\natives near Breckenrldge, Mich.\nRuth White and Miss Blue of\nDeshler, were callers at the Martin\nWhite home on Tuesday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. Dan Light of Mc\nClure were guests of Mr. and Mrs.\nBernard Katon on Saturday night.\nHave you returned Sterling's\nmilk bottles and reminded your\nneighbor to do likewise?\nGrand Rapids jj\nMarkets\nHeavy hens\nHeavy stags\nLight hens\nLight stags\nHeavy broilers\nLight ^rollers\nDucks\nVeal...\nEggs\nCream\nCom\nWheat\n2*\n19\n.-18\n12\n29\n24\n...._ 19\n9 to 11\n22\n3\u00ab\n$1. to 1.06\n11.00\n40 to 42\ny*","height":"29560","width":"21384"}}
